	<title>Math234Fa24-Midterm2</title>
	<exercise>
		<introduction>
			<p>
				Let <m>f(x,y) = 4xy+\cos(\pi x) + y^3.</m>
			</p>
		</introduction>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the tangent plane to <m>f</m> at <m>(2,-1).</m>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Use the tangent plane to <m>f</m> at <m>(2,-1)</m> to approximate the value of <m>f(2.1, -0.9).</m>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</task>
	</exercise>
	<exercise>
		<introduction>
			<p>
				Suppose <m>f(u,v)</m> is differentiable and <m>u=x-y</m> and <m>v=y-x</m>. Find <me>\dfrac{\partial
							f}{\partial x} +\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial y}.</me> <m>w=1,</m> <m>x=2</m> and <m>y=-1.</m>
			</p>
		</introduction>
	</exercise>
	<exercise>
		<introduction>
			<p>
				Let <m>f(x,y) = e^{x^2 - y} + 2\sqrt{y}</m>.
			</p>
		</introduction>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the directional derivative of the function <m>f(x,y)</m> at the point <m>(2,4)</m> in the direction of the point <m>(3,-1).</m> That is, find the directional derivative at <m>(2,4)</m> as a particle is moving from <m>(2,4)</m> to <m>(3,-1).</m>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Based on your answer from (a), is the function <m>f(x,y)</m> increasing (that is, is the value of the function getting larger), or decreasing (that is, is the value of the function getting smaller) in that direction at the point <m>(2,4)</m>?
				</p>
			</statement>
				<choices multiple-correct="no">
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								Increasing
							</p>
						</statement>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								Decreasing
							</p>
						</statement>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								Staying constant
							</p>
						</statement>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								Cannot be determined with the information provided
							</p>
						</statement>
					</choice>
				</choices>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					In what direction does <m>f</m> have the maximum rate of change at the point <m>(2,4)</m>? Write your answer as a <term>unit</term> vector. Make sure to write your final answer in the provided answer box. Answer:
				</p>
			</statement>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What is the maximum rate of change of <m>f</m> at <m>(2,4)</m>? Make sure to write your final answer in the provided answer box. Answer:
				</p>
			</statement>
		</task>
	</exercise>
	<exercise>
		<introduction>
			<p>
				Consider the function <me>f(x,y) = 3x^2y + y^3-3y.</me>
			</p>
		</introduction>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find all critical point(s) of <m>f(x,y)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Classify each critical point you found in (a) as a local maximum, local minimum, or saddle point.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</task>
	</exercise>
	<exercise>
		<introduction>
			<p>
				Find the absolute maximum and minimum values of the function <m>f(x,y)= xy</m> subject to the constraint <m>x^2+4y^2=2</m>.
			</p>
		</introduction>
	</exercise>
	<exercise>
		<introduction>
			<p>
				Compute the following integrals.
			</p>
		</introduction>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					<m>\displaystyle\int_{-2}^1 \int_{0}^{y} xe^{y^3}\, dx \, dy</m>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					<m>\displaystyle\int_0^1 \int_y^{\sqrt{2-y^2}} \sqrt{x^2+y^2} \, dx \, dy</m>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					<m>\displaystyle\int_0^{\pi/2}\int_{x}^{\pi/2} \dfrac{\sin(y)}{y}\, dy\, dx</m>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</task>
	</exercise>
	<exercise>
		<introduction>
			<p>
				Write down triple integrals that represent the volume of the following solids. You do <term>NOT</term> need to evaluate the integrals. Please note that this question has three parts, (a) and (b) on this page, and (c) on the next page.
			</p>
		</introduction>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The solid in the first octant that is bounded by the coordinate planes and the plane <m>x+y+z=3.</m>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The solid that lies in the first octant, above the paraboloid <m>z = x^2+y^2,</m> and below the paraboloid <m>z = 8-x^2-y^2.</m>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The solid that lies below the cone <m>z = -\sqrt{x^2+y^2},</m> and between the spheres <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=9</m> and <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=16.</m>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</task>
	</exercise>
